      <div class="about-text reveal">
        <p>I'm a <strong>Computer Science Engineering student</strong> with a deep interest in <strong>Artificial Intelligence, Generative AI, and Large Language Models</strong>. My work sits at the intersection of solid computer science fundamentals — data structures, system design, databases — and applied AI, where I build things like retrieval-augmented generation pipelines, computer-vision-based health tools, and AI agents.</p>
        <p>Alongside AI/ML, I'm equally comfortable across the full stack — designing REST APIs with FastAPI and Flask, building interfaces in React, and modeling data in SQL, PostgreSQL and MongoDB. I care about shipping systems that are not just accurate, but usable, fast and well-engineered end to end.</p>
        <p>My goal is to grow into an <strong>AI Engineer role at a product-based technology company</strong>, where I can work on systems used at scale and keep learning at the edge of what generative AI can do.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="about-block reveal">
      <h3 class="about-block-title">My journey so far</h3>
      <p>My interest in computer science started the way it does for a lot of engineers — with curiosity about how the software on my screen actually worked underneath. That curiosity turned into a habit of building: small C and Java programs first, then web pages, then full applications with a backend and a database behind them. Somewhere along the way I got pulled into machine learning, and once I trained my first model and watched it make a correct prediction, I was hooked. That moment is a big part of why I chose to specialize in AI/ML and Generative AI rather than stop at "just" full stack development.</p>
        <p>Over the course of my B.Tech, I've tried to treat every course and every project as a chance to go one level deeper — not just to pass an exam, but to actually understand the "why" behind data structures, database design, operating systems and networks. That fundamentals-first approach is what let me pick up Generative AI concepts like RAG, embeddings and agentic workflows quickly once I started exploring them on my own, well beyond what any single course covered. Maintaining a 9.21 CGPA throughout has mattered to me, but it's always been a side effect of that curiosity rather than the goal itself.</p>
        <p>The AI/ML virtual internship with Infosys Springboard gave me my first structured exposure to real-world ML workflows — data cleaning, model evaluation, and the kind of iterative debugging that textbooks rarely prepare you for. It confirmed something I'd already started to suspect: I enjoy the applied side of AI far more than the purely theoretical side. I want to build things people can actually open in a browser and use, not just notebooks that produce a metric.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="about-block reveal">
      <h3 class="about-block-title">What I focus on</h3>
      <div class="focus-grid">
        <div class="focus-item">
          <div class="focus-ic">🧠</div>
          <h4>Generative AI &amp; LLMs</h4>
          <p>Designing RAG pipelines, working with embeddings and vector search, and orchestrating LLM-powered workflows with LangChain and LangGraph.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="focus-item">
          <div class="focus-ic">🩺</div>
          <h4>AI for healthcare</h4>
          <p>Applying computer vision and generative models to problems like skin condition analysis and symptom-based diagnosis support.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="focus-item">
          <div class="focus-ic">🛠️</div>
          <h4>Full stack engineering</h4>
          <p>Building complete systems — React front ends, FastAPI/Flask/Express back ends, and SQL/NoSQL data layers — not just isolated scripts.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="focus-item">
          <div class="focus-ic">📐</div>
          <h4>Strong fundamentals</h4>
          <p>Treating data structures, algorithms, DBMS, OS and networking as the foundation everything else — including AI — is built on top of.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="about-block reveal">
      <h3 class="about-block-title">How I like to work</h3>
      <p>I tend to start any new project by writing down the actual problem in plain language before I open an editor — it's easy to jump straight to "which library should I use" and lose sight of who the system is actually for. From there I like to build a rough end-to-end version early, even if it's unpolished, so I can see the whole pipeline working before I spend time refining any one piece. That habit came from a few early projects where I over-engineered a single component and only later realized the overall flow didn't hold together.</p>
      <p>I'm comfortable working independently — most of my AI/ML and full stack projects have been self-driven, which means I've had to be my own reviewer, tester and documentation writer. That's taught me to be honest about a project's weak points rather than just its demo-ready parts, and it's part of why I care about things like clean READMEs, sensible commit history and code that a reviewer at a product company could actually read.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="about-block reveal">
      <h3 class="about-block-title">Beyond the code</h3>
      <p>Outside of coursework and projects, I spend a lot of time reading about new AI research and product launches — trying to understand not just what a new model or technique can do, but why it was built that way. I'm an active problem solver on LeetCode, partly for interview preparation and partly because I genuinely enjoy the puzzle of finding a cleaner algorithm. I also enjoy explaining technical concepts to classmates and juniors; teaching something is usually the fastest way I've found to discover the gaps in my own understanding.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="about-block reveal">
      <h3 class="about-block-title">Where I'm headed</h3>
      <p>My near-term goal is to land an internship or entry-level role at a <strong>product-based technology company</strong> — somewhere like Google, Microsoft, NVIDIA, Apple, Ericsson or Cisco — where I can work on AI-driven products used by real people at real scale, alongside engineers I can learn from. Longer term, I want to grow into a role where I'm designing the systems, not just implementing them: someone who understands both the machine learning underneath a product and the full stack required to ship it responsibly and reliably.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

